Manual Crack Classification¶

1. Shuffle all Images into Train and Test Folder¶

The number of labeled image is only 120.

In [2]:
! find /Users/ray/Desktop/crack-images/LCMS-Range-Labeled/annotations -type f -regex ".*xml" | wc -l

     120

It's far from enough for us to train the model using nuerual network. We still need to label the test data manuallly. There are in total 13745 images in the test folder.

In [3]:
! find /Users/ray/Desktop/crack-images/LCMS-Range -type f -regex ".*JPG" | wc -l

   13745

Ideally we need at least 10000 samples to train our model. Since each original image actually contains three 410 $\times$ 410 small images by cropping and splitting, we can use 4000 images to generate 12000 samples to train our model.

We noticed that the labeled train data is essentially a subset of the unlabeled data, for example:

In [4]:
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import load_img

We find that LCMS-Range-Labeled/images/000000670000.JPG and LCMS-Range/172J0HYQF90/000000000000/000000670000.JPG are essentailly the same.

In [6]:
path = "/Users/ray/Desktop/crack-images/LCMS-Range/172J0HYQF90/000000000000/000000670000.JPG"
img = img_to_array(load_img(path)).astype(int)
plt.figure(figsize=(4,8))
plt.imshow(img)
plt.show()

Therefore we cannot use the lebeled data as our train-set to avoid repeatness.

Since all the unlabeled data are in seperate folder and some have the same name, we need to reorganize the structure of the folder by simply splitting all images into two folders: train and test. train folder should contains 3751 images and test foler should contains 1000 images.
